\section{\texorpdfstring{Impact on the
Standard\hyperref[impact-on-the-standard]{}}{Impact on the Standard}}\label{impact-on-the-standard}

This is a pure language extension. It:

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  changes no existing valid program's meaning (code that does not
  combine \VERB|\KeywordTok{auto}| with \VERB|\KeywordTok{override}| is
  unaffected);
\item
  makes well-formed a category of declarations that are ill-formed today
  (\VERB|\KeywordTok{auto}\NormalTok{ f}\OperatorTok{()} \KeywordTok{override}|
  with no trailing-return-type on a virtual function);
\item
  requires no library changes;
\item
  requires no changes to the ABI or object model --- an
  \VERB|\KeywordTok{auto}\NormalTok{ … }\KeywordTok{override}| function
  has the same type, mangling, and vtable slot it would have had if its
  return type were written out by hand.
\end{itemize}

There are no breaking changes and no deprecations.

\section{\texorpdfstring{Implementation
experience\hyperref[implementation-experience]{}}{Implementation experience}}\label{implementation-experience}

The feature requires no novel analysis. A conforming compiler already:

\begin{enumerate}
\def\labelenumi{\arabic{enumi}.}
\tightlist
\item
  resolves which base function(s) a member overrides (to validate
  \VERB|\KeywordTok{override}| and covariance), and
\item
  has the overridden function's return type available at that point.
\end{enumerate}

Implementing the proposal amounts to: when a virtual function's declared
return type is the bare \VERB|\KeywordTok{auto}| placeholder and
\VERB|\KeywordTok{override}| is present, set the function's return type
to the overridden function's return type (after the existing override
resolution) instead of entering body-based deduction. No implementation
experience exists yet; the author believes a prototype in a major
compiler is straightforward and intends to pursue one.

\section{\texorpdfstring{Future
directions\hyperref[future]{}}{Future directions}}\label{future}

The following are intentionally \textbf{out of scope} for this paper but
are natural follow-ups:

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  \textbf{\VERB|\KeywordTok{decltype}\OperatorTok{(}\KeywordTok{auto}\OperatorTok{)}|
  overrides.} Could be defined to copy the base type with its value
  category, though the practical benefit over \VERB|\KeywordTok{auto}|
  is small.
\item
  \textbf{Deduced covariant return types.} Allowing
  \VERB|\KeywordTok{auto}| to deduce a covariant type from the body
  (rather than copying the base type exactly) was considered and
  rejected for R0 in favor of a simpler rule; it could be revisited.
\item
  \textbf{Dropping the \VERB|\KeywordTok{override}| requirement.}
  Permitting deduction for any overriding function was rejected (see
  {[}design.trigger{]}); revisiting it would require a story for silent
  overrides and accidental coupling.
\end{itemize}

